<DOC><DOCNO> AP890719-0085 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-89 1158EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-Afghanistan     07-19 0198</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Afghanistan,0202</SECOND><HEAD>Afghan Rebels Claim 880 Government Soldiers Captured</HEAD><DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Afghan guerrillas said today theycaptured 880 communist troops, including a handful of officers, whenthey overran several government posts in the eastern province ofPaktia.   The offensive was launched Sunday, but the Afghan News Agency,which is controlled by the guerrillas and based in Pakistan, saiddetails of the fighting didn't reach Pakistan until Wednesday. Asecond Afghan source, independent of the rebel groups in Islamabad,confirmed the report.   The fighting centered on posts 10 miles west of theheavily-fortified town of Khost, 15 miles from the Pakistan border.Many of the weapons sent through Pakistan to guerrilla positions inAfghanistan pass through Paktia province.   The Afghan News Agency described the fighting as ``one of thebiggest ever offensives against the communist regime troops inPaktia.''   The report said U.S.-backed insurgents also captured weapons andmilitary vehicles, including seven tanks, five of which were inworking order.   In another report, the agency said up to 400 government troopswere killed or wounded in an attack last week on the border town ofSpinboldak in southern Afghanistan. The attack could not beindependently confirmed.</TEXT></DOC>